[
    {
        "content": "<p>Where should <code>⅟</code> be used?</p>",
        "id": 453229083,
        "sender_full_name": "Martin Dvořák",
        "timestamp": 1721667621
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>is that even in mathlib? this only would be useful when you don't want to use <code>⁻¹</code> for one reason or another...</p>",
        "id": 453231351,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1721668219
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>or if for some reason raising to the power <code>-1</code> doesn't give inverses</p>",
        "id": 453231527,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1721668255
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but i can't imagine when that would be the case</p>",
        "id": 453231619,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1721668282
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>E.g., if you want to work in a ring but assume that a certain element has an inverse.</p>",
        "id": 453232020,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1721668412
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Like <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Z[\\frac12]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1901em;vertical-align:-0.345em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8451em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.345em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 453232385,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1721668515
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess we could have divinv monoid instances for such rings. But it becomes quite forced</p>",
        "id": 453232707,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1721668594
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the difference is that you can have <code>⅟x</code> for elements <code>x</code> in a structure that does not have a general inversion <code>x ↦ x⁻¹</code>. E.g., you can assume <code>[Invertible (2 : R)]</code> when <code>R : Ring</code> and then use <code>⅟2</code> in <code>R</code>, whereas <code>2⁻¹</code> would not type-check, because <code>R</code> has no inversion (you'd have to work with the units instead).</p>",
        "id": 453233727,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Stoll",
        "timestamp": 1721668864
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>will we want to apply this to matrices as well? i seem to recall there being a discussion mentioning the fact that <code>Inv</code> does exists for general matrices, despite it not being a total inverse...</p>",
        "id": 453235105,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1721669209
